##Bermuda

###Bermuda 1869-1872 First Issue



<div style="width:80%;margin:0 auto">
<img src="http://localhost/egypt/bermuda/1007.jpg" style="width:98%" />
<p style="font-size:smaller">
RED LARGE RARE "BERMUDA" FLEURON{{footnote:1}} ON QUADRUPLE-RATE COVER TO G.B.; 20 Nov. 1843 E (seal lost; some corner-wear and small tears re-backed with 'magic' tape) to London (redirected to Weymouth with "4d paid" for 1-2oz weight) having a mostly very fine red large St. Georges "BERMUDA" fleuron (PM2) nicely placed on the flap. Fleurons struck in clearly red ink are very hard to find and often poor strikes; this is remarkably clear.    	£500
{{auction: Cavendish January 2009, The Geoffrey Osborn Bermuda Collection}}
</p>
</div>

<div style="width:80%;margin:0 auto">
1773
<img src="http://localhost/egypt/bermuda/1008.jpg" style="width:98%" />
<p style="font-size:smaller">
IRELAND ISLAND - EARLY COVER TO G.B. WITH V. FINE "HAMILTON/+BERMUDA+" (PM4) C.D.S.; V. fine 4 Feb. 1844 EL (interesting family letter from a serving soldier; ref. smallpox in Bermuda, etc.) sent from "Ireland Island, Bermuda" to Surrey, endorsed "via Halifax" having a lovely strike of the black 6 Feb. PM4 "HAMILTON/+BERMUDA+" c.d.s. nicely placed on the flap, charged the "1/-" Packet rate.The naval P.O. on Ireland Island had no direct connection to the Bermuda P.O. otherwise this letter would have had the rare 1842-45 Ireland Island PM4 c.d.s. Exhibition Quality.  
{{auction: Cavendish January 2009, The Geoffrey Osborn Bermuda Collection}}
</p>
</div>

<div style="width:80%;margin:0 auto">
1773
<img src="http://localhost/egypt/bermuda/1010.jpg" style="width:98%" />
<p style="font-size:smaller">
NAVAL MAIL TO G.B. FROM H.M. SHIPS ANCHORED AT IRELAND ISLAND; 20 Apr. 1844 & 2 May 1848 pair of stampless ELs (one in an env.) from "H.M.S. Eurydice, Bermuda" [at the Dockyard, Ireland Is.] or from "H.M.S. Vesuvius, Bermuda" [also at Ireland Is.?] to London/Banbury, each charged "1/-" (the first with v. fine black boxed London "PACKET LETTER" nicely placed on the front. The first with intriguing letter ref. a cask containing "$16,000" consigned on the "R.M.S. Tweed" on the ship that carried the letter; the other from a Naval Officer who is "on the West India Station" ref. 40,000 miles voyaging under sail (though in a steamer), a visit to Carriacou island, and "...we have sent to Jamaica for all our missing letters which we hope to receive before we leave Bermuda". 
Fine and unusual Naval pair sent direct via other naval vessels and so 
without Bermuda P.O. marks. (2 covers)    	£150
{{auction: Cavendish January 2009, The Geoffrey Osborn Bermuda Collection}}
</p>
</div>


<div style="width:80%;margin:0 auto">
