<p style="font-size:smaller">
RED "BERMUDA/PAID" DATESTAMP (P1) ON LOCAL 1d-RATE COVER; Attractive long 11 Oct. 1845 env. (some flaps reduced) from "G. James Tucker" (filing note inside) addressed to the Attorney General in "Hamilton" and endorsed "O.H.M. Service" but prepaid the internal 1d postage with a red manuscript "1d" at right and a very fine (for this) red P1 St. Georges "BERMUDA/oPAIDo" c.d.s. also on the front. Rare thus; 
early local mail is seldom seen, and this is as fine a strike of 
this mark as we have seen. [Ex Ulrich, 1989.]    	£750
{{auction: Cavendish January 2009, The Geoffrey Osborn Bermuda Collection}}
</p>
</div>

<div style="width:80%;margin:0 auto">
1773
<img src="http://localhost/egypt/bermuda/1013.jpg" style="width:98%" />
<p style="font-size:smaller">
THE RARE RED "BERMUDA/SHIP LETTER" OF ST. GEORGES ON COVER EX G.B.; 14 July 1846 EL (discoloured file-fold clear of marks and address; two small holes in address-panel, one just clear of mark) from "London" sent to "Thomas F. Ewing Esqr., Hamilton, Bermuda" and endorsed "p. [ship] Enterprize, Capt. Freeman" (arrived Bermuda 14 Sept.) and charged "4" (arrival Ship letter rate) with a very fine red St. Georges S1/I "BERMUDA/SHIP LETTER" mark (crossed by clean fold) nicely placed on the front. Only about 15 examples are known, of which this [illustrated in Forand & Freeland's 1995 "Bermuda Mails to 1865"
 is one of the clearest. Exhibition Quality. [Ex Sir Henry Tucker, 1978 - sold for £750.]    	£1500
{{auction: Cavendish January 2009, The Geoffrey Osborn Bermuda Collection}}
</p>
